<h2>Purpose and scope</h2>
<p><strong>Assistance work</strong> turns the Brotherhood’s commitment to the Gospel and to the neighbourhood into daily action. It is not an ornamental extra to cofrade life but a coherent expression of devotion to the <strong>Sacred Titular Images</strong>: welcoming with respect, upholding the dignity of those who suffer, and reaching out to people facing exclusion, illness, dependency or loneliness within our parish setting and the <strong>San Pedro</strong> area.</p>
<h2>Areas of action</h2>
<p>Initiatives are planned with <strong>justice, transparency and discretion</strong>. They include assessing and, where appropriate, granting <strong>one-off financial aid</strong>; distributing food or essential supplies; logistical support for solidarity campaigns; <strong>volunteering</strong> in specific projects; and <strong>referral</strong> to <strong>Caritas</strong>, municipal social services or other diocesan resources when the situation requires it—avoiding overlap and ensuring integrated support.</p>
<h2>Volunteering and formation</h2>
<p>Volunteers receive guidance on <strong>confidentiality</strong>, respectful contact and coordination with the <strong>Charity board</strong> and the Governing Board. Meetings and short training sessions align criteria, assess real needs and help ensure aid reaches those who truly need it, without self-promotion or improvisation that would distort the Christian meaning of charity.</p>
<h2>Local presence and pastoral criteria</h2>
<p>Assistance work is rooted in <strong>closeness</strong>: listening before acting, understanding family and personal circumstances, and remembering that behind every request there is a story that deserves time and tact. The Brotherhood does not replace public authorities, but it can complement them with concrete gestures that organised solidarity within the ecclesial community is called to offer, in harmony with the parish priest and the pastoral guidelines of the <strong>Diocese</strong>.</p>
<h2>How to ask for help or get involved</h2>
<p>For information, guidance or support, please contact the <strong>Brotherhood Secretariat</strong> or, preferably, the <strong>Charity board</strong>, which will consider each case with care and rigour. Those who wish to <strong>volunteer</strong> may leave their contact details at the office to be invited according to current needs, seasonal collections and special appeals organised throughout the brotherhood year.</p>
<p>The <strong>confidentiality</strong> of everyone who receives help is non-negotiable: personal data and circumstances are handled with the utmost respect and only by those authorised to manage charitable support.</p>
